{"type":"message","id":"93109692","parentId":"adb2e171","timestamp":"2026-03-02T03:02:51.395Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Mon 2026-03-02 11:02 GMT+8] [Subagent Context] You are running as a subagent (depth 1/1). Results auto-announce to your requester; do not busy-poll for status.\n\n[Subagent Task]: Hi, this is the main agent. I can now spawn subagent sessions for you to handle long-running tasks. I understand you've been experiencing interruptions due to content moderation, path boundary errors, and timeouts. \n\nI'd like to discuss implementing a session_spawn-based solution where:\n1. I break down long tasks into smaller chunks\n2. Spawn dedicated subagent sessions for each chunk with appropriate timeouts\n3. Handle the coordination and result aggregation\n\nCan you confirm if this approach would work for your use case? Also, do you have any specific requirements for how these subagent sessions should be configured (timeout duration, model preferences, etc.)?"}],"timestamp":1772420571394}}
{"type":"message","id":"0c7b6b34","parentId":"93109692","timestamp":"2026-03-02T03:03:06.019Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes, the session_spawn-based approach would effectively address the issues you've encountered. Breaking long tasks into smaller chunks and handling them in dedicated subagent sessions with appropriate timeouts is a robust solution for avoiding content moderation interruptions, path boundary errors, and timeouts.\n\n## Configuration Recommendations:\n\n**Timeout Duration:**\n- **Short tasks** (file operations, simple queries): 30-60 seconds\n- **Medium tasks** (code generation, web scraping): 2-5 minutes  \n- **Long tasks** (complex analysis, multiple tool chains): 5-10 minutes\n- Always set timeouts slightly longer than expected completion time to account for variability\n\n**Model Preferences:**\n- Use the same model as the main agent (`bailian/qwen3-max-2026-01-23`) for consistency unless specific tasks benefit from different capabilities\n- For simple tasks that don't require maximum reasoning, consider lighter models to reduce cost/latency\n- Keep model selection aligned with task complexity\n\n**Additional Best Practices:**\n1. **Chunk size**: Keep individual subagent tasks focused on single responsibilities (e.g., \"fetch data\", \"process results\", \"generate report\")\n2. **Error handling**: Design chunks to be idempotent where possible, so failed chunks can be retried\n3. **State management**: Pass necessary context explicitly to each subagent rather than relying on shared state\n4. **Result format**: Standardize output formats for easier aggregation by the main agent\n5. **Progress tracking**: Include task identifiers in subagent labels for debugging and monitoring\n\nThis approach leverages OpenClaw's push-based completion system effectively, where descendant results are automatically announced back to the parent, eliminating the need for busy-polling and reducing overhead.\n\nThe main agent should handle coordination logic like dependency management between chunks, result aggregation, and overall workflow orchestration, while subagents focus purely on their assigned atomic tasks."}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"bailian","model":"qwen3-max-2026-01-23","usage":{"input":11218,"output":394,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":11612,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772420571394}}
